g.text: Scenario 2: Double Fault (Recoverable if Handler Exists)
Root Causes: Specific Triple Fault Triggers
PIC Default vs Remapped: Vector Collision Detail

div.p: Fault Event e.g. divide-by-zero executing user code int or CPU exception
IDT Lookup CPU reads vector N from IDT (properly set up) Gate descriptor valid Handler addr resolved
CPU Pushes Frame (kernel stack, ESP from TSS) EFLAGS, CS, EIP [SS, ESP if ring-3] Error code (if applicable)
Handler Executes pusha saves registers C handler runs cleanly No nested fault occurs EOI sent (if IRQ)
iret Resumes Pops EIP, CS, EFLAGS [ESP, SS for ring-3] Interrupted code resumes System continues
First Fault e.g. GPF, page fault or bad segment access during kernel execution
Handler Faults! Kernel exception handler itself raises an exception (stack overflow, null ptr, bad IDT gate, etc.)
CPU Invokes Vector 8 Double Fault = exception 8 CPU looks up IDT[8] Requires valid gate Error code pushed = 0
Double Fault Handler (vector 8, error code=0) Must NOT fault again Print diagnostics Halt: cli; hlt Recoverable here

Common Causes of Handler Fault Stack overflow in ISR (ESP invalid) Null pointer dereference in handler BSS not zeroed (global = garbage) pusha/popa mismatch corrupt ESP Missing volatile bad MMIO write
Original Fault Any exception or IRQ fires at the wrong moment (before IDT / during setup)
Double Fault Attempt to invoke double fault handler (IDT[8]) also fails invalid gate, or handler faults again
TRIPLE FAULT CPU has NO fallback Cannot invoke any handler Cannot print any message Cannot signal the OS Asserts RESET# pin
QEMU: Instant Reboot Physical HW: Cold reset No error message No stack trace Appears as: system restarts QEMU flag: -d int shows last interrupt before reset

PIC Not Remapped Default: IRQ0 (timer) vector 8 Vector 8 = Double Fault handler First timer tick (55ms after sti): timer fires IRQ0 CPU sees vector 8 invokes "double fault handler" this was your timer code, not a real double fault handler immediate nested fault TRIPLE FAULT
Fix: pic_remap(0x20, 0x28) BEFORE calling sti

Stack Overflow in Handler Handler uses too much stack OR kernel stack not set up OR TSS.ESP0 points to old process ESP becomes invalid mid-handler next push triggers stack fault (#SS) fault-in-fault = double fault double fault handler uses same broken stack faults again TRIPLE FAULT
Fix: Per-process kernel stacks Update TSS.ESP0 on every switch Check KERNEL_STACK_SIZE 4KB

IDT Not Set Up Before sti IDTR points to zero / garbage OR IDT has invalid gate entries Any interrupt after sti fires: CPU reads IDT at address 0 (real-mode IVT invalid gates) GPF trying to load bad selector fault-in-fault double fault IDT[8] also invalid triple TRIPLE FAULT
Fix: idt_setup_all() + lidt THEN pic_remap() THEN sti always in this order

BEFORE pic_remap() BROKEN IRQ0 (Timer) vector 8 DOUBLE FAULT! IRQ1 (Keyboard) vector 9 Invalid TSS IRQ2 (Cascade) vector 10 Seg Not Present IRQ3 (COM2) vector 11 Stack Fault IRQ4 (COM1) vector 12 Stack Fault IRQ5 (LPT2) vector 13 GP Fault IRQ6 (Floppy) vector 14 PAGE FAULT! IRQ7 (LPT1) vector 15 Reserved IRQ8 (RTC) vector 112 (0x70)

AFTER pic_remap(0x20,0x28) CORRECT IRQ0 (Timer) vector 32 safe IRQ1 (Keyboard) vector 33 safe IRQ2 (Cascade) vector 34 safe IRQ3 (COM2) vector 35 safe IRQ4 (COM1) vector 36 safe IRQ5 (LPT2) vector 37 safe IRQ6 (Floppy) vector 38 safe IRQ7 (LPT1) vector 39 safe IRQ8 (RTC) vector 40 safe IRQ15 (Spurious) vector 47 safe CPU Exceptions: vectors 031 (no collision)

div.h1: Log all interrupts to file; last entry before reboot = triple fault cause
div.p:
qemu-system-i386
-drive format=raw,file=os.img
-serial stdio
-d int 2>interrupts.log
div.h1: Signature of PIC-not-remapped triple fault in log:
v=08 e=0000 i=0 cpl=0 IP=0008:001000xx double fault (timervec8)
v=08 e=0000 i=0 cpl=0 IP=0008:001000xx double fault handler faults
div.p:
qemu-system-i386 ... -s -S gdb kernel.elf -ex "target remote :1234"
-ex "break idt_setup_all" -ex "continue"
